---
/**
 * About Cedar — single editorial spread.
 *
 * No three-up card grid. No i/ii/iii numbering. One asymmetric
 * layout: a long block of editorial prose on the left, one
 * featured transcript fragment treated as the pull-quote on the
 * right. Reads like a magazine sidebar, not a feature-list.
 */
import '../styles/cedar.css';
---
<section class="cedar-about" id="cedar">
  <div class="cedar-about__inner">

    <div class="cedar-about__prose">
      <p class="cedar-about__byline">On Cedar &mdash;</p>

      <p class="cedar-about__lede">
        Most economic models are confident about the wrong things. They&rsquo;ll print a 3-decimal multiplier for a tribal economy whose supply chain has never been observed, and they&rsquo;ll do it in the same font as the multiplier for an interstate manufacturing corridor that&rsquo;s been studied to death.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cedar is the part of every Lumecon platform that refuses to pretend. It reads what you upload &mdash; a payroll detail, a council agenda, a chapter audit &mdash; and asks you to confirm the assumption the model is about to use, before the model uses it. If your last year&rsquo;s study said supply-chain leakage was 48%, and the default is 38%, Cedar surfaces that &mdash; not as an alert dialog, as a sentence in the run.
      </p>

      <p>
        It writes the assumption ledger as you work. By the time the export lands, the ledger is at the top of the file: every source, every vintage, every override you made, in plain language a council member or grant reviewer can read without opening the spreadsheet.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cedar runs in a per-project sandbox. Project and file names are hashed before any provider call leaves the platform; your real user ID never appears upstream. The version you&rsquo;ve been talking to in the hero is scoped to questions about the demo &mdash; no upstream call, no memory between sessions.
      </p>
    </div>

    <aside class="cedar-about__pull">
      <div class="cedar-about__pull-mark" aria-hidden="true">&ldquo;</div>
      <p class="cedar-about__pull-q">
        I&rsquo;ll model the supply chain as 38% in-region. Your call &mdash; the audit you ran last spring used 52%.
      </p>
      <p class="cedar-about__pull-a">
        Use 52.
      </p>
      <p class="cedar-about__pull-tag">A real exchange, on a draft run.</p>
    </aside>

    <footer class="cedar-about__foot">
      <p class="cedar-about__motto">
        Cedar won&rsquo;t think <em>for</em> you. It thinks <em>with</em> you.
      </p>
      <a href="#contact" class="btn">Ask us about Cedar</a>
    </footer>
  </div>
</section>
